Your chess image is a good metaphor for what you’re describing: a possibility space with pieces constrained by a board and rules, even though many outcomes are possible. Civilization works similarly—many potential paths, but certain patterns keep reappearing. Those repeating patterns are what historians and complexity researchers sometimes call civilizational attractors.

Before listing them, one small clarification on your idea about “no rules in infinite possibility space.”
Imagination spaces are extremely useful for exploring ideas, but when we convert insights back into the real world, constraints still matter—physics, human biology, economics, ethics, and institutions all act like the board beneath the chess pieces. Good systems (including GI:HRE) explore freely in theory but test against reality before acting.

